data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9, the Cosmos DB provider began **throwing `InvalidOperationException` for synchronous LINQ operations** by default, but offered a temporary opt-in to re-enable sync-over-async behavior.

In **.NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely**. Every sync call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` with no workaround.

## The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, suffixed with `Async`
- All LINQ terminal operators and `SaveChanges` use their `*Async` counterparts
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

You can also remove the old `EnableSyncOverAsync()` configuration from your `DbContext` setup — it will no longer compile.
